title: SpaceX launches a pair of Intelsat satellites on expendable Falcon 9
summary: SpaceX successfully launched a second pair of C-band replacement satellites for Intelsat over the weekend on the final flight of a frequently used Falcon 9 booster.

title: Booster 7 resumes static fire testing as SpaceX ramps up Starship production
summary: Booster 7 is set to resume its static fire test campaign as soon as Monday with a short firing of half of its engines in what is hoped to be the significant event before the long-awaited 33-engine static fire test. This milestone will put the Super Heavy booster one step closer to being ready for Starship’s first orbital flight.

title: The first cubesat to fly and operate at the Moon has successfully arrived
summary: "That is a huge, huge step for the agency."

title: The oracle who predicted SLS’s launch in 2023 has thoughts about Artemis III
summary: An unbiased industry source is back for more space policy spitballing.

title: CAPSTONE enters lunar orbit
summary: A NASA-funded cubesat successfully completed a maneuver to enter orbit around the moon Nov. 13.

title: ABL Space Systems on verge of first orbital launch attempt
summary: ABL Space Systems could launch the first test flight of its one-ton class RS1 rocket from Alaska as soon as this week, after securing a launch license from the Federal Aviation Administration, the company said Sunday.

title: Delayed NASA Venus mission looks for a reprieve
summary: The head of a Venus mission delayed at least three years by NASA in response to problems with another mission says she will attempt to shorten that delay.

title: SpaceX expends Falcon 9 booster for the first time in almost three years
summary: For the first time since January 2020, SpaceX has intentionally expended a Falcon 9 booster instead of attempting to recover the rocket...

title: Engineers assessing hurricane-damaged insulation before Artemis launch Wednesday
summary: NASA managers cleared the agency’s leak-bedeviled Artemis moon rocket for the start of another countdown early Monday, but engineers must resolve questions about hurricane-damaged insulation before the huge booster can be cleared for blastoff on an unpiloted moonshot.

title: ESA seeks funding for navigation technology programs at ministerial
summary: The European Space Agency is requesting several hundred million euros at its upcoming ministerial council meeting for new satellite navigation technologies from low Earth orbit to the moon.
